===Etymology===
{{m|en|hello|Hello}} (first attested in 1833), from {{m|en|holla}}, {{m|en|hollo}} (attested 1588). This variant of {{m|en|hallo}} is often credited to [[w:Thomas Edison|Thomas Edison]] as a coinage for telephone use, but its appearance in print predates the invention of the telephone by several decades.

Ultimately from a variant of Old English ''[[eala#Old_English|ēalā]]'', such as ''[[hela#Old_English|hēlā]]'', which was used colloquially in that time similarly to how "hey" or "hi" is used nowadays. Thus, equivalent to a compound of ''[[hey]]'' and ''[[lo]]''.

Possibly influenced by the {{etyl|goh|en}} and {{etyl|osx|en}} verb {{m|goh|halon}}, {{m|goh|holon||to bring something, to gather}}, akin to {{etyl|en|-}} {{m|en|hale}} or {{m|en|hail}}. More at {{l|en|hallo}}.

